(a 
                           〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉

                     ) signifies properly the white cloth which is set by the Minister of Baptism upon the head of a Child newly Anointed with Chrism after his Baptism: Now it is vulgarly taken for the white cloth put about or upon a Child newly Christened, in token of his Baptism; wherewith the woman used to shrowd the Child, if dying within the Month; otherwise it is usually brought to Church at the day of Purification. Chrisomes in the Bills of Mortality are such Children as die within the Month of their Birth, because during that time they use to wear the Chrisom cloth.

